1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,685
Let's talk about name scopes.

2

00:00:02,685  -->  00:00:05,240
To see an example of this in action,

3

00:00:05,240  -->  00:00:09,325
we're going to write a function that's called print function.

4

00:00:09,325  -->  00:00:13,160
We'll say def print_function and then we'll

5

00:00:13,160  -->  00:00:20,480
say local_var_in_function = I am a local variable.

6

00:00:20,480  -->  00:00:22,400
That will be set as a string.

7

00:00:22,400  -->  00:00:26,275
Then we'll print that variable right here.

8

00:00:26,275  -->  00:00:29,875
Then we'll execute our function below.

9

00:00:29,875  -->  00:00:32,600
When we run this function,

10

00:00:32,600  -->  00:00:34,500
we'll see a print out,

11

00:00:34,500  -->  00:00:36,170
I am a local variable.

12

00:00:36,170  -->  00:00:41,390
But if we were to try and print the variable inside of the function, which is this one,

13

00:00:41,390  -->  00:00:45,835
and we try to do this, we say print_local_var_in_function,

14

00:00:45,835  -->  00:00:48,335
can you guess what's going to happen when we do this?

15

00:00:48,335  -->  00:00:51,350
When we run this, we'll see a NameError,

16

00:00:51,350  -->  00:00:53,045
and it will say name,

17

00:00:53,045  -->  00:00:56,150
local_var_in_function is not defined.

18

00:00:56,150  -->  00:01:01,510
This is because local var and function only exists within the print function.

19

00:01:01,510  -->  00:01:04,430
Trying to access it outside of the function

20

00:01:04,430  -->  00:01:07,745
will result in an error because it's out of scope.

21

00:01:07,745  -->  00:01:11,795
What does a global scope for a variable look like instead?

22

00:01:11,795  -->  00:01:13,470
Let's use another example.

23

00:01:13,470  -->  00:01:18,345
We'll say global_var = I am global.

24

00:01:18,345  -->  00:01:19,870
That'll be set as a string,

25

00:01:19,870  -->  00:01:24,045
and then we'll define a print_global function

26

00:01:24,045  -->  00:01:29,480
where we'll print that variable that we've defined up at the top called global_var,

27

00:01:29,480  -->  00:01:35,730
then we'll execute our print_global_function below.

28

00:01:35,730  -->  00:01:39,250
When we run this, can you guess what the output of this is going to be?

29

00:01:39,250  -->  00:01:40,790
When we execute this cell,

30

00:01:40,790  -->  00:01:43,020
we'll see I am global.

31

00:01:43,020  -->  00:01:47,350
Also, if we try and print global_var like this,

32

00:01:47,350  -->  00:01:50,950
can you guess what we'll be able to see when we just do this?

33

00:01:50,950  -->  00:01:53,100
If you said, I am global, you're right.

34

00:01:53,100  -->  00:01:57,560
We'll also see the same variable string printed out.

35

00:01:57,560  -->  00:02:02,640
This works because we've defined this global variable outside of the function,

36

00:02:02,640  -->  00:02:06,960
and then it's able to pull from this global environment.

37

00:02:06,960  -->  00:02:11,180
But here, because this is locked within the function,

38

00:02:11,180  -->  00:02:15,540
we cannot access it outside of the scope of the function.

39

00:02:15,540  -->  00:02:21,580
But here, because the global variable exists outside of the function scope,

40

00:02:21,580  -->  00:02:23,080
it's now in a global scope,

41

00:02:23,080  -->  00:02:26,945
so we're able to call that from within the function and outside of the function.

42

00:02:26,945  -->  00:02:30,590
Now, let's talk about name hiding and shadowing.

43

00:02:30,590  -->  00:02:34,930
Sometimes local variables can have the same name as global variables.

44

00:02:34,930  -->  00:02:37,790
This is called name hiding or shadowing,

45

00:02:37,790  -->  00:02:41,630
and the local variable takes precedence within its scope.

46

00:02:41,630  -->  00:02:44,190
Basically, what's happening here is that we're

47

00:02:44,190  -->  00:02:47,710
declaring a globally accessible variable at the top,

48

00:02:47,710  -->  00:02:50,350
which we're going to see in a second called name,

49

00:02:50,350  -->  00:02:52,595
and that has a global scope.

50

00:02:52,595  -->  00:02:55,010
Inside, the print name function,

51

00:02:55,010  -->  00:02:56,490
which you'll also see next,

52

00:02:56,490  -->  00:02:59,410
will declare a variable, also called name,

53

00:02:59,410  -->  00:03:02,925
but this has a local scope. Let's do that right now.

54

00:03:02,925  -->  00:03:07,800
We're going to say name = I am a global name.

55

00:03:07,800  -->  00:03:11,830
Name is set as a string and then we're going to define

56

00:03:11,830  -->  00:03:16,950
a print name_function with def print_name and then we're

57

00:03:16,950  -->  00:03:21,960
going to say name = I am a local (name).

58

00:03:21,960  -->  00:03:23,820
Then we're going to print(name),

59

00:03:23,820  -->  00:03:25,725
and then we're going to run

60

00:03:25,725  -->  00:03:33,355
our print name_function and then we're also going to print the variable of name.

61

00:03:33,355  -->  00:03:37,060
Can you guess what these two outputs are going to be?

62

00:03:37,060  -->  00:03:40,740
They're going to print two different things or maybe two of the same things.

63

00:03:40,740  -->  00:03:44,140
But can you guess what the output of print_name will

64

00:03:44,140  -->  00:03:47,820
be and print variable of name will be?

65

00:03:47,820  -->  00:03:49,720
When we execute this code,

66

00:03:49,720  -->  00:03:52,710
we'll see the first statement,

67

00:03:52,710  -->  00:03:53,870
which is print_name,

68

00:03:53,870  -->  00:03:57,320
which is printing the name says I am a local name,

69

00:03:57,320  -->  00:04:01,500
and then print variable name right here,

70

00:04:01,500  -->  00:04:03,800
says I am a global name.

71

00:04:03,800  -->  00:04:07,240
Although there is a global variable name at the top,

72

00:04:07,240  -->  00:04:10,380
the function defines a local variable

73

00:04:10,380  -->  00:04:16,500
here within the same name shadowing the global variable.

74

00:04:16,500  -->  00:04:18,480
Outside of the function,

75

00:04:18,480  -->  00:04:21,425
the global variable remains unchanged.

76

00:04:21,425  -->  00:04:24,680
When we redeclare a variable called name,

77

00:04:24,680  -->  00:04:26,960
even though it has a global scope,

78

00:04:26,960  -->  00:04:31,620
the function will take this to be what we want name to be,

79

00:04:31,620  -->  00:04:37,820
and then it will assume that we are writing name as a variable within that function,

80

00:04:37,820  -->  00:04:40,760
and we only want to call that not the global scope,

81

00:04:40,760  -->  00:04:42,900
if they have the same name.

82

00:04:42,900  -->  00:04:47,340
But when we call this outside of the function scope with print(name),

83

00:04:47,340  -->  00:04:49,810
that's why it prints I am a global name,

84

00:04:49,810  -->  00:04:51,550
as opposed to I am a local name,

85

00:04:51,550  -->  00:04:53,490
which is function specific.

86

00:04:53,490  -->  00:04:56,750
Finally, let's talk about the global keyword.

87

00:04:56,750  -->  00:05:02,030
Expanding upon our local and global scope knowledge from the previous sections,

88

00:05:02,030  -->  00:05:05,650
let's say we want to modify a global variable from within a function.

89

00:05:05,650  -->  00:05:12,515
You might be wondering, how do we do that since global and local are separate scopes?

90

00:05:12,515  -->  00:05:15,615
We can use something called the global keyword to accomplish this.

91

00:05:15,615  -->  00:05:17,720
But just a word of caution.

92

00:05:17,720  -->  00:05:22,040
Be very cautious and careful with this approach as it can make

93

00:05:22,040  -->  00:05:27,560
debugging harder mixing global and local scopes like you're going to see in a second.

94

00:05:27,560  -->  00:05:32,040
First, let's see an example where we're going to be

95

00:05:32,040  -->  00:05:36,660
declaring a globally scoped variable that will be a counter variable,

96

00:05:36,660  -->  00:05:41,420
and then we're going to be writing an increment function that will overwrite

97

00:05:41,420  -->  00:05:43,260
the counter variable by using

98

00:05:43,260  -->  00:05:47,820
the global keyword on the counter variable and incrementing it by plus one.

99

00:05:47,820  -->  00:05:50,565
Let's see what that looks like in action.

100

00:05:50,565  -->  00:05:53,020
We'll declare a variable called counter,

101

00:05:53,020  -->  00:05:55,695
and we'll set that equal initially to zero.

102

00:05:55,695  -->  00:06:00,120
Then we'll define a function called increment and then

103

00:06:00,120  -->  00:06:04,645
we're going to declare a global variable called counter.

104

00:06:04,645  -->  00:06:08,700
Then we're going to say counter += 1.

105

00:06:08,700  -->  00:06:14,565
Then we will call this function and execute it.

106

00:06:14,565  -->  00:06:19,475
We'll run this function by calling the increment and run this whole operation.

107

00:06:19,475  -->  00:06:24,425
Once we execute this, if we were to then print(counter),

108

00:06:24,425  -->  00:06:27,275
can you guess what the output of counter will be?

109

00:06:27,275  -->  00:06:29,655
Counter is now one.

110

00:06:29,655  -->  00:06:31,470
If you said one, you're right.

111

00:06:31,470  -->  00:06:34,675
Notice how it now is no longer zero.

112

00:06:34,675  -->  00:06:38,020
By declaring counter as a global variable

113

00:06:38,020  -->  00:06:42,580
here within the global keyword inside of the increment function,

114

00:06:42,580  -->  00:06:46,320
which is within this, any changes made inside

115

00:06:46,320  -->  00:06:50,360
of increment affect the global counter variable above,

116

00:06:50,360  -->  00:06:53,940
even though counter would otherwise be a locally scoped variable.

117

00:06:53,940  -->  00:06:55,840
If you remember from earlier,

118

00:06:55,840  -->  00:06:58,520
if we were working with variables inside the function,

119

00:06:58,520  -->  00:07:00,200
that would be function specific.

120

00:07:00,200  -->  00:07:03,580
But because we use this global keyword that then tells

121

00:07:03,580  -->  00:07:07,160
Python to look outward to the global scope,

122

00:07:07,160  -->  00:07:09,920
and then to increment

123

00:07:09,920  -->  00:07:13,160
the actual globally scoped counter variable and

124

00:07:13,160  -->  00:07:17,780
not a locally scoped variable within the function.
